{{Infobox scientist |name = Philippa Fawcett |image = Phillipafawcett.jpg |image_size = 200px |caption = Philippa Garrett Fawcett (1868-1948) |birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1868|4|4}} |birth_place = |death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1948|6|10|1868|4|4}} |death_place = |residence = UK |citizenship = |nationality = British |ethnicity = |fields = [[Mathematician]] |workplaces = [[London County Council]] |alma_mater = [[Newnham College, Cambridge]] & [[Bedford College, London]] |doctoral_advisor = <!--There was not PhD at Cambridge until 1919--> |academic_advisors = [[Ernest William Hobson]] |doctoral_students = |notable_students = |known_for = First woman ranked "above [[Senior Wrangler]]" |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences = |influenced = |awards = |religion = |signature = <!--(filename only)--> |footnotes = }} '''Philippa Garrett Fawcett''' (4 April 1868 – 10 June 1948) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[mathematician]] and [[educationalist]].
==Family== Philippa Garrett Fawcett was the daughter of the [[suffragist]] [[Millicent Fawcett]] and [[Henry Fawcett]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]], Professor of [[Political Economy]] at [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]] and [[United Kingdom Postmaster General|Postmaster General]] in [[William Ewart Gladstone|Gladstone's]] government. Her aunt was [[Elizabeth Garrett Anderson]], the first English female doctor. When her father died, she and her mother went to live with Millicent's sister [[Agnes Garrett]], who had set up an interior design business on [[Gower Street, London|Gower Street]], [[Bloomsbury]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/bloomsbury-project/articles/events/conference2011/crawford.pdf |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>
==Education== Philippa Fawcett was educated at [[Bedford College, London]]<ref name="Yale University Press">{{Cite book|title=Victorian Bloomsbury by Rosemary Ashton|url=https://books.google.com/?id=u9gDEx6iZ5EC&pg=PA235&lpg=PA235&dq=a+second+generation+of+feminists+attended+Bedford+College+after+its+removal+from+bloomsbury#v=onepage&q=a%20second%20generation%20of%20feminists%20attended%20Bedford%20College%20after%20its%20removal%20from%20bloomsbury&f=false|accessdate=11 June 2018|isbn=9780300154474|last1=Ashton|first1=Rosemary|date=2012-11-13}}</ref> (now [[Royal Holloway]]) and [[Newnham College, Cambridge]] which had been co-founded by her mother. In 1890 she became the first woman to obtain the top score in the Cambridge [[Mathematical Tripos]] exams. The results were highly publicised, with the top scorers receiving great acclaim. Her score was 13 per cent higher than the second highest, but she did not receive the title of [[senior wrangler]], as only men were then ranked and women were listed separately. Women had been allowed to take the Tripos since 1880, after [[Charlotte Angas Scott]] was unofficially ranked as eighth wrangler. When the women's list was announced Fawcett was described as "above the senior wrangler". No woman was officially awarded the first position until Ruth Hendry in 1992.
Coming amidst the [[women's suffrage]] movement, Fawcett's feat gathered worldwide media coverage, spurring much discussion about women's capacities and rights. The lead story in the ''[[The Daily Telegraph|Telegraph]]'' the following day said:
{{centered pull quote| Once again has woman demonstrated her superiority in the face of an incredulous and somewhat unsympathetic world... And now the last trench has been carried by Amazonian assault, and the whole citadel of learning lies open and defenceless before the victorious students of Newnham and Girton. There is no longer any field of learning in which the lady student does not excel.<ref>Series, Caroline. "And what became of the women?", Mathematical Spectrum, Vol. 30 (1997/8), 49-52</ref>}}
==Career== Following Fawcett's achievement in the Tripos, she won the [[Marion Kennedy]] scholarship at [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]]<ref name=newn>[http://www.newn.cam.ac.uk/about/history/biographies/ Marion Kennedy], Newnham College, Retrieved 22 June 2017</ref> through which she conducted research in [[fluid dynamics]]. Her published papers include "Note on the Motion of Solids in a Liquid".<ref>{{cite journal |last = Fawcett |first = Philippa |date = 1893 |title = Note on the Motion of Solids in a Liquid |url = http://resolver.sub.uni-goettingen.de/purl?PPN600494829_0026/DMDLOG_0035 |journal = Quarterly Journal of Pure and Applied Mathematics |volume = 26 |pages = 231–258 |access-date = 2018-05-04 }}</ref> She was appointed a college lecturer in Mathematics at Newnham College, a position she held for 10 years.<ref>[http://www.agnesscott.edu/lriddle/women/fawcett.htm "Philippa Fawcett", Biographies of Women Mathematicians], [[Agnes Scott College]]</ref> In this capacity, her teaching abilities received considerable praise. One student wrote:
{{centered pull quote| What I remember most vividly of Miss Fawcett's coaching was her concentration, speed, and infectious delight in what she was teaching. She was ruthless towards mistakes and carelessness... My deepest debt to her is a sense of the unity of all truth, from the smallest detail to the highest that we know<ref>Newnham College Roll Letter, February 1949, 46-54. Newnham College Archives.</ref> }}
Fawcett left Cambridge in 1902, when she was appointed as a lecturer to train mathematics teachers at the [[normal school|Normal School]] in [[Johannesburg]], South Africa,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140311193735/http://www.slonfawcett.org.uk/userfiles/documents/2012%20philippa%20fawcett%20biography.pdf South London Fawcett Group Biography]</ref> now [[University of Pretoria#Groenkloof, Pretoria|part of the University of Pretoria]]. She remained there, setting up schools in South Africa, until 1905, when she returned to Britain to take a position in the administration of education for [[London County Council]]. At the LCC, in her work developing [[secondary school]]s, she attained a high rank. Denied a Cambridge degree by her sex, she was one of the [[steamboat ladies]] who travelled to Ireland between 1904 and 1907 to receive an [[ad eundem degree|''ad eundem'']] University of Dublin degree at [[Trinity College, Dublin|Trinity College]].<ref name="steamboat">{{cite web |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/theme/61643 |title=Steamboat ladies (''act.'' 1904–1907) |last1=Parkes |first1=Susan M. |work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]] |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]}}</ref>
Philippa Fawcett maintained strong links with Newnham College throughout her life. The Fawcett building (1938) was named in recognition of her contribution to the college, and that of her family. She died on 10 June 1948, two months after her 80th birthday, a month after the Grace that allowed women to be awarded the Cambridge BA degree received royal assent.<ref>Stephen Siklos, official [[Newnham College|Newnham]] biography of [http://www.newn.cam.ac.uk/about-newnham/college-history/biographies/content/philippa-fawcett/ Philippa Fawcett], 2004</ref>
